<p>Any PTO you didn’t use during the calendar year cannot be carried over to another calendar year. </p>

<h6>Eligibility</h6>
<p>PTO starts to accrue upon hire or transfer into a regular full-time position.  Interns, temporary employees, and part-time employee are not eligible for PTO.</p>

<h6>Availability</h6>
<p>PTO accruals are available for use in the pay period following your completion of 30 days of employment. Once 30 days of employment have been reached PTO, you can use your PTO.   With your manager's approval, you may use PTO time that will be earned later in the same calendar year. You may not use PTO time from future years. It is the responsibility of you and your manager to track availability and use of PTO.</p>

<h6>Duration of PTO</h6>
<p>Because we are a small company and each employee plays a unique and vital role, we recommend that you limit each PTO period to a maximum of 5 business days. If you need to take off a longer period of time, please notify your manager as early as possible. </p>

<h6>PTO &amp; Overtime</h6>
<p>You may take PTO in increments as low as a half day (four hours). PTO is not included in the calculation of overtime.</p>

<p>Occasional time off from work in increments less than four hours (excluding time missed because you are late to work) for reasons such as personal appointments will be paid without requiring the use of PTO.  However, this time off is not included in the calculation of overtime. (Medical and dental appointments should be scheduled as to not conflict with your work schedule.  Where this is not possible, arrangements should be made with a manager.)</p>

<p>As a small company, we depend greatly on each other, and unplanned absences can sometimes disrupt the progress we’re making. So, try to keep unscheduled PTO to a minimum and schedule lengthy PTO (around 5 business days or more) in advance. If you need to be out for a health-related issue, we may ask you to provide a statement from a health-care provider.</p>

<p>Payment upon Termination
If you leave Noodle Education, Inc., we will pay you for accrued, unused PTO. If you leave Noodle Education, Inc. with a negative PTO balance, we will deduct the value of that PTO from your final paycheck.
Holidays
Every day is like a holiday at Noodle. Nevertheless, you get to stay home or do whatever you like on the holidays below:</p>

<ul>
<li>New Year’s Day*</li>
<li>Martin Luther King Day</li>
<li>President’s Day</li>
<li>Memorial Day</li>
<li>Independence Day*</li>
<li>Labor Day</li>
<li>Thanksgiving Day + Friday after Thanksgiving Day</li>
<li>Christmas Day*</li>
</ul>

<p>If a holiday falls on a Sunday, we’ll observe it on the following Monday; if it falls on a Saturday, we’ll observe it on the preceding Friday.  If any holiday falls on a Tuesday or Thursday, we’ll also take off the preceding Monday or following Friday.  If a holiday falls on a Wednesday, it will be at management’s discretion as to whether the preceding or following day is also taken off. Also, we’ll take off an extra day when Christmas Day or New Year’s Day falls on a weekend. Part time employees are not paid for company holidays.</p>

<h6>Short-Term Disability</h6>
<p>PAll employees are covered by short-term disability insurance. Let us know if you have questions about the details and limitations of this coverage.</p>

<h6>Bereavement Leave Policy</h6>
Noodle wants to be supportive of employees during the difficult time following the loss of someone you care about. As a regular full-time employee, you can take up to five days of paid bereavement leave for the death of an immediate family member. For purposes of this policy, immediate family members include an employee’s spouse/domestic partner, child, parent/guardian, sibling, grandchild, or in-laws.  You will receive three days for the death of an aunt, uncle or grandparent.</p>

<h6>Jury Duty</h6>
<p>Noodle recognizes an employee’s civic responsibility to serve on a jury if requested to do so. As a regular full-time employee, you will be paid your full salary for up to five days, and as a regular part-time employee you will be paid your hourly rate for up to three days. If you are required to serve additional time on a jury, then you will be permitted to take unpaid leave for the duration of the jury service.  You must submit a copy of your jury summons to Human Resources when you receive it and report to work on days when you are not on jury duty or on partial days when the court doesn't require your presence.</p>

<h6>Military Leave</h6>
<p>In accordance with the Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act (“USERRA”) and state law where applicable, Noodle respects the right and obligations of employees to serve in the United States Armed Forces and offers leave for its employees in that capacity.  Arrangements should be made with a manager when military commitments conflict with an employee's work schedule.  </p>

<h6>Unpaid Personal Leave of Absence</h6>
<p>If you need extended time off from work for personal or other reasons and which do not qualify as Family and Medical Leave, you may be permitted to take an unpaid leave of absence at Noodle’s sole discretion. You may not take any leave of absence in excess of six months. WE will not grant a leave of absence if you have fewer than six months (180 calendar days) of continuous service.</p>

<p>An approved unpaid personal leave of absence does not assure you the right to return to work at Noodle or to return to the job you held. Although we will try to place you in a job, we are not obligated to do so. If we do offer you a position at the end of the leave and you do not accept it, we will consider that your resignation without notice.</p>

<p>When on an unpaid personal leave of absence, you are responsible for maintaining your benefit premiums. If you are on unpaid leave for more than six weeks, your benefits coverage will be discontinued and offered through COBRA.</p>

<h6>Family and Medical Leave Act</h6> 
<p>Given its small size, Noodle is not obligated to follow federal Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) requirements, but we do anyway.  FMLA provides unpaid leave and certain protections for you if you meet eligibility requirements for certain life circumstances.</p>

<p>What can FMLA be used for?</p>

<ul>
<li>For the birth, adoption or placement for foster care of a son or daughter and to care for such child.</li>
<li>To care for the employee’s spouse, son, daughter or parent who has a serious health condition.</li>
<li>Because of a serious health condition that makes the employee unable to perform any one or more of the essential functions of his or her job.</li>
</ul>

<p>Any leave taken under one or more of these circumstances will be counted against the employee’s total available FMLA leave for that leave year. You should submit FMLA requests in writing at least 30 days in advance, when the leave is foreseeable, or as soon as is practical thereafter.  </p>

<h6>Unpaid Leave</h6>
<p>Noodle Education, Inc. grants leave without pay to eligible employees for up to twelve weeks in any twelve-month period. The time off is not paid, unless the employee is taking PTO or disability leave concurrently with unpaid leave. Any time off taken under the PTO policy will run concurrently with this Unpaid Family and Medical Leave policy.  </p>

<p>Eligibility for Unpaid Leave: To be eligible for unpaid leave, the employee must have been employed full-time by Noodle Education, Inc. for at least twelve months before the date the leave begins. </p>

<p>Reasons for Taking Unpaid Leave: Eligible employees are entitled to take unpaid leave for any of the following reasons:</p>

<ul>
<li>The birth of a child and to take care of the new-born child;  </li>
<li>The placement of a child in the employee’s home for adoption, foster care, or guardianship, and to care for the newly placed child;</li>
<li>The care of an employee’s immediate family member who has a serious health condition (immediate family includes the employee’s spouse or domestic partner, children and parents but not a parent “in law”); </li>
<li>The employee’s own serious health condition that renders the employee unable to perform his or her job with or without reasonable accommodation (the first twelve weeks will be counted toward unpaid leave although the employee may be disabled longer).</li>
</ul>

<p>Leave to care for a newborn child or for a newly placed child must conclude within twelve months after the birth or placement.</p>

<p>Spouses co-employed by Noodle Education, Inc. will be limited to a combined total of twelve weeks of unpaid leave for the following reasons:</p>

<ul>
<li>Birth and care of a child; or</li>
<li>Placement of a child for adoption, foster care or guardianship, and to care for the newly placed child.</li>
</ul>

<p>The primary caregiver is the person at home who cares for the child.  Only one parent (or guardian) can be the primary caregiver at a 
given time, but both parents (or guardians) can serve as the primary caregiver at different times.  You are the primary caregiver if:</p>

<ul>
<li>You are the person who cares for the child immediately following the child’s birth, adoption, foster placement, or guardian placement;</li>
<li>You assume the role of the primary caregiver after your spouse or partner has been the primary caregiver and returned to work; or </li>
<li>You are the spouse or partner of a mother who has a complicated postnatal pregnancy and is unable to care for the child.</li>
</ul>


<p> The following medical certification rules apply to employees requesting unpaid leave:</p>

<p>If the leave is needed to care for a sick child, spouse or parent, the employee must provide a certification from the health care provider that states:</p>

<ul>
<li>Date of commencement of the serious health condition;</li>
<li>Probable duration of the condition;</li>
<li>Estimated amount of time the health care provider will provide care; and</li>
<li>Confirmation that the serious health condition warrants the participation of a family member.</li>
</ul>

<p>If the leave is needed for the employee's own serious health condition, the employee must provide a certification from a health care provider that states:</p>

<ul>
<li>Date of commencement of the serious health condition;</li>
<li>Probable duration of the condition; and</li>
<li>A statement that the employee is unable to perform the functions of his or her position because of the serious health condition.</li>
</ul>

<p>Compensation and Benefits During Leave
An employee taking unpaid leave will be allowed to continue participating in any health and welfare benefit plans in which he or she was enrolled prior to the first day of the leave.  </p>

<p>Reinstatement Following Unpaid Leave 
A leave of absence, especially an extended one, does not guarantee that your position will be available to you after the end of your leave.  Each case will be treated individually and upon your return, every effort will be made to give you the best available job for which you are qualified by experience, ability and seniority.  </p>

<p>Effect of State Law
Noodle Education, Inc. complies with all requirements, prohibitions, and other provisions of the state and local laws applicable in areas where it operates or does business.  If a state law entitles an employee to more generous benefits than does this unpaid leave policy, the employee will receive the more generous benefits.</p>
</section>
<section id="workers-compensation">
