<h2>OTHER IMPORTANT STUFF</h2>

<h6>Equal Employment Opportunity </h6>
<p>
Noodle Education, Inc. is committed to ensuring equal employment opportunity for all employees for all of our employment practices. This means we don’t discriminate. Noodle is an equal opportunity employer and conducts all business activities without regard to age, ethnicity, gender, pregnancy, disability, marital status, national origin, race, religion, sexual orientation, as well as other classifications protected by applicable federal, state or local laws.</p>

<p>We believe strongly in this so if you have any question or concern regarding this policy, speak with a member of the Senior Team right away. If any person is found to have violated this policy will be disciplined, which could include termination. Any applicant or employee filing a complaint or assisting in the investigation of a complaint is protected from reprisal, interference, and discrimination.</p>

<h6>Fair Labor Standards Act</h6>
<p>
Employees will be classified as exempt or non-exempt under the Fair Labor Standards Act.  All employees, except employees holding executive, administrative, or professional positions as well as outside salespersons and computer programmers, are covered by the minimum wage and overtime provisions of the law  (covered employees are referred to as "non-exempt employees").   Non-exempt employees are entitled to overtime pay at a rate of one and a half times their regular rate for work hours in excess of 40 hours per week or at a rate consistent with applicable state law.</p>

<p>It is our policy to comply with the salary basis requirements of the Fair Labor Standards Act. Therefore, we prohibit all company managers from making any improper deductions from the salaries of exempt employees.  We want employees to be aware of this policy and that the company does not allow deductions that violate the Fair Labor Standards Act.  </p>

<h6>Immigration</h6>
<p>
In compliance with the Immigration Reform and Control Act, only those individuals eligible to work in the United States will be employed.  All individuals will be required to submit proof of their identity and employment eligibility.  Employees will also be required to complete and sign Form I-9 issued by the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.  If you are authorized to work in this country for a limited period of time, you will be required to submit proof of your employment authorization and sign another Form I-9 at the end of the period in order to remain employed.</p>
